.SH "NAME"
ndn_xmltondnb \- convert XML into ndn binary encoded data (ndnb)
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBndn_xmltondnb\fR [\-hw] [\-d \fIdict\fR] \fIfile\fR \fI\&...\fR
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
The \fBndn_xmltondnb\fR converts standard text\-based XML into ndn binary encoded (ndnb) form\&.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.PP
\fB\-h\fR
.RS 4
Print usage and exit\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-d\fR \fIdict\fR
.RS 4
Augment the built\-in DTAG dictionary with the named file (format like tagname\&.csvdict)\&. May be repeated\&. Use this if you have defined some ndnb formats of your own\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-w\fR
.RS 4
Toss UDATA content consisting of only whitespace\&. This is useful if there has been white space added for display purposes (newlines and indentation, for example)\&. For NDNx data (e\&.g\&. Interest and ContentObject) you probably always want this\&.
.RE
.SH "ARGUMENTS"
.sp
The named files should contain xml data\&. Use \fB\-\fR to specify filter mode (read standard input, write standard output)\&.
.SH "OUTPUT"
.sp
If not using filter mode (\fB\-\fR for the file name), the output file names are generated from the input file names, using the extension \fB\&.ndnb\fR\&. Status and diagnostic messages appear on standard error\&.
.sp
The output may be converted back into regular XML by using the \fBndn_ndnbtoxml\fR utility\&.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.PP
